            <div class="HowToTitle4">Troubleshooting</div>
            <p>
                This is a simple setup that doesn't require adjustments or maintenance to the actual parts. They either work or they don't. There are two items in the system
                that could go bad over time. Since there are two, let's take one of them out of the equation. They are the GM HEI Module that is mounted to the external
                mounting plate, and the internal (to the Distributor) Reluctor Pickup. They are the only two things that can possibly go bad. So, to take the Internal Distributor
                Reluctor Pickup out of the game, with a Digital Multimeter set to LOW Ohms, measure across the two leads that are connected to the GM HEI Module. Disconnect
                them first. Your reading for a good Reluctor Pickup should be between .200 and .400 ohms. If you have that, and your system has been running great until then, it
                is the GM HEI Module. This is a VERY reliable system.
            </p>
